This Week's Special Feature:
Christmas Shopping for your favorite Agoran
by Horace Undernut, TSR's business consultant

As we all know, it's never too early to begin Christmas shopping. And
this year promises to be the best ever for friends and family of
Agoran players. I am joined by Dr. Gorog Sprzmysl, consumer expert.

TSR: So, Doctor, what have our readers to look forward to this
shopping season?

GS: There are a lot of good ideas out there as companies jump onto the
business bandwagon that is Nomic. A smart consumer can snap up some
great bargains.

TSR: I see you have selected some items to show us. What is this here?

GS: The Franklin Mint (TM) has issued a commemorative coin for Agora's
fifth anniversary. Minted from .999 proof silver, the obverse bears
a portrait of Peter Suber while the reverse has Agora's symbol and its
motto "USQUAM PER LEGES". At only US$9.99, it's in the reach of even
the most poverty-stricken Player.

TSR: Magnificent detail in Suber's hair. And what do we have here?

GS: Perfect for the disgruntled ex-Player, the Agora toilet-seat cover
makes a statement every time you go to the john. It runs for US$24.95.

TSR: I see you've saved the best for last. This is truly something.

GS: Ah, yes, the Agora commemorative chess set. With marble and jet
figures with gold highlights, on a teak and mahogany board, this is a
gift for the Agora conoisseur. As you can see, each piece is modeled
after a Player of Agora. On the white side, Steve Gardner is the king,
General Chaos is the queen, elJefe and Chuck Carroll are the
rooks, Michael Norrish and Oerjan are the bishops, Blob and Morendil
are the knights, and the pawns are miniature mousetraps. 

TSR: Fascinating. And the black side?

GS: There you have Ronald Kunne as the king, David Wagner as the
Queen, Wes Contreras and KoJen as the rooks, Vlad and David Nicol as
the bishops, Swann and Andre as the knights, and the pawns are
miniature walruses.

TSR: And the cost?

GS: It can all be yours for only US$499.99.

TSR: I'll get one for my office. Thanks for your time, good Doctor.



